window.docContents[143].resolve({"/Lecture-2___-Predicate-Logic-and-Sets/The-Universal-Quantifier/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-2___-Predicate-Logic-and-Sets--The-Universal-Quantifier":{"contents":"To prove ∀ x, P x, consider an arbitrary element and prove the proposition at it. The tactic intro, which introduced implications in Lecture 1, also introduces universal quantifiers.\n\nexample (α : Type) (P Q : α → Prop)\n    (h : ∀ x, P x ∧ Q x) : ∀ x, P x := by\n  intro a\n  exact (h a).left\n\n\nThe proof also uses the elimination rule. A hypothesis h : ∀ x, P x ∧ Q x is a function that returns a proof of P a ∧ Q a for each a, so the application h a instantiates it at a. This parallels Lecture 1, where a proof of an implication was a function on proofs. The tactic specialize instantiates a universal hypothesis in place.\n\nexample (α : Type) (P Q : α → Prop) (h : ∀ x, P x → Q x)\n    (a : α) (hPa : P a) : Q a := by\n  specialize h a\n  exact h hPa\n\n\nThe universal quantifier distributes over conjunction. The proof combines the rules for the quantifier with the rules of Lecture 1 for conjunction and the biconditional.\n\ntheorem forall_and_distrib (α : Type) (P Q : α → Prop) :\n    (∀ x, P x ∧ Q x) ↔ (∀ x, P x) ∧ (∀ x, Q x) := by\n  constructor\n  · intro h\n    constructor\n    · intro a\n      exact (h a).left\n    · intro a\n      exact (h a).right\n  · intro h a\n    exact ⟨h.left a, h.right a⟩\n\n\n","context":"Formal Software Verification\u0009Lecture 2: Predicate Logic and Sets","header":"2.2. The Universal Quantifier","id":"/Lecture-2___-Predicate-Logic-and-Sets/The-Universal-Quantifier/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-2___-Predicate-Logic-and-Sets--The-Universal-Quantifier"}});